Data Types in Java

1. Introduction to Data Types
- Definition: A data type defines the kind of data a variable can hold and how much memory it needs.
- Analogy: Think of data types as different sizes and shapes of lockers in a hostel:
- Small lockers for tiny items (byte).
- Standard lockers for everyday items (int).
- Big lockers for huge items (long).
- Special lockers for letters (char) or switches (boolean).

2.Categories of Data Types
Java data types are divided into two main categories:
  - Primitive Data Types → Basic building blocks (8 types).
  - Non‑Primitive Data Types → Reference types like Strings, Arrays, Classes, Objects

 Key Points:
- Primitives store values directly in memory (stack).
- They are fast and efficient.
- Each has a fixed size

3 Non‑Primitive (Reference) Data Types
  Strings
- Analogy: A sentence locker that holds words.
- Technical: Objects of String class, immutable.
  String name = "Shaminder";


  Arrays
- Analogy: A row of lockers all of the same type.
- Technical: Fixed‑size collection of elements.
  int[] marks = {90, 85, 88};



Final Takeaway for Students
- Data types define what kind of data a variable can hold.
- Primitive types (8) → basic lockers with fixed size.
- Non‑primitive types → advanced lockers storing references, flexible, can have methods.
- Memory model: Primitives → stack; References → heap.




Data Types in Java
│
├── Primitive (8 types)
│   ├── Numeric
│   │   ├── Integer Types
│   │   │   ├── byte (1 byte)
│   │   │   ├── short (2 bytes)
│   │   │   ├── int (4 bytes)
│   │   │   └── long (8 bytes)
│   │   └── Floating-Point Types
│   │       ├── float (4 bytes, ~7 digits precision)
│   │       └── double (8 bytes, ~15 digits precision)
│   │
│   ├── Character
│   │   └── char (2 bytes, Unicode)
│   │
│   └── Boolean
│       └── boolean (true/false)
│
└── Non-Primitive (Reference Types)
    ├── String
    ├── Array
    ├── Class
    ├── Object
    ├── Interface
    ├── Collections (ArrayList, HashMap, etc.)
    └── Wrapper Classes (Integer, Double, etc.)



